# Security Checklist

## Configuration Security [cite: 35]
- [ ] Store secrets in environment variables or dedicated secret management systems [cite: 35]
- [ ] Never commit secrets to version control [cite: 35]
- [ ] Implement secret rotation policies [cite: 35]
- [ ] Use different credentials for different environments [cite: 35]
- [ ] Encrypt sensitive configuration values [cite: 35]

## Authentication & Authorization [cite: 35]
- [ ] Implement proper authentication mechanisms [cite: 35]
- [ ] Use OAuth 2.0 or OpenID Connect where appropriate [cite: 35]
- [ ] Implement role-based access control (RBAC) [cite: 35]
- [ ] Follow the principle of least privilege [cite: 35]
- [ ] Implement multi-factor authentication (MFA) for sensitive operations [cite: 35]

## Data Protection [cite: 35]
- [ ] Encrypt data at rest [cite: 35]
- [ ] Encrypt data in transit (TLS/HTTPS) [cite: 35, 36]
- [ ] Implement proper key management [cite: 36]
- [ ] Sanitize and validate all inputs [cite: 36]
- [ ] Implement output encoding to prevent XSS attacks [cite: 36]
- [ ] Apply proper database security controls [cite: 36]

## API Security [cite: 36]
- [ ] Implement rate limiting [cite: 36]
- [ ] Set appropriate timeouts [cite: 36]
- [ ] Use API keys/tokens with proper scopes [cite: 36]
- [ ] Validate and sanitize all API inputs [cite: 36]
- [ ] Implement proper error handling that doesn't leak sensitive information [cite: 36]

## Infrastructure Security [cite: 36]
- [ ] Use container security scanning [cite: 36]
- [ ] Implement network segmentation [cite: 36, 37]
- [ ] Apply security hardening to containers and hosts [cite: 37]
- [ ] Use Web Application Firewalls (WAF) where appropriate [cite: 37]
- [ ] Implement proper egress filtering [cite: 37]

